ncashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Somme, Picardy, France":"Somme, Picardie, Frankrijk","Barton, Lancashire, England":"Barton, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1150–1195":"1150–1195","1160–Female":"1160–Deceased","1160–1212":"1160–1212","1170–1222":"1170–1222","1162–1220":"1162–1220","–Female":"Deceased","1120–1170":"1120–1170","1125–1212":"1125–1212","1220":"1220","1120":"1120","1195":"1195","1162":"1162","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","Abt 1162":"about 1162","1125":"1125","1212":"1212","about 1149":"about 1149","1222":"1222","Abt 1170":"about 1170","Bolton, Lancashire, England":"Bolton, Lancashire, England","Barton, Preston, Lancashire, England":"Barton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Somme, Picardy, France":"Somme, Picardie, France","Barton, Lancashire, England":"Barton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Barton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places called with Old English <i>bere</i> or <i>bær</i> ‘barley’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’, i.e. an outlying grange. Compare   Barwick  . The name is also found in Ireland, where it has been Gaelicized as <b>de Bartún</b>.","Polish (<b>Bartoń</b>); Czech and Slovak (mainly <b>Bartoň</b>): from a pet form of the personal name Polish <i>Bartłomiej</i>, Czech <i>Bartoloměj</i>, Slovak <i>Bartolomej</i>, from Latin <i>Bartholomaeus</i> (see   Bartholomew  ). This surname is also found in Germany."],"variants":[{"name":"Barwick","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Berwick or Barwick, for example in Northumberland, Norfolk, Somerset, and Yorkshire, from Old English <i>bere</i> ‘barley’ + <i>wīc</i> ‘outlying farm building’, i.e. a granary lying some distance away from the main settlement.","North German: habitational name from a place called Berwick, near Soest, in Westphalia."]}]},{"name":"Matthew","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name of the Christian evangelist, author of the first gospel in the New Testament. His name is a form of the Hebrew name <i>Mattathia</i>, meaning ‘gift of God’, which is fairly common in the Old Testament, being rendered in the Authorized Version in a number of different forms: <i>Mattan(i)ah</i>, <i>Mattatha(h)</i>, <i>Mattithiah</i>, <i>Mattathias</i>, and so on. In the Authorized Version, the evangelist is regularly referred to as <i>Matthew</i>, while the apostle chosen to replace Judas Iscariot is distinguished as   Matthias .  A related name from the same Hebrew roots, but reversed, is   Jonathan .  Throughout the English-speaking world <i>Matthew</i> has been particularly popular since the 1970s."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathew","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Matthew ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Matthew De Barton was born in 1150, in Barton, Lancashire, England, his father, Leysing de Barton II, was 30 and his mother, Agatha of Barton, was 25. He had at least 5 daughters with Mary of Barton. He died in 1195, in Barton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1150–1195":"1150–1195","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","116